Intro

This is a set of R examples for my personal reference beyond this course.

Loading Data and Packages

  1. Install the here package.
  2. Download and read data files into R.
  3. Perform an exploratory data analysis.

To install here we can just type:

install.packages("here")

to read data,

here()
read.csv()

For examples: to load the 2021 ginkgo lead data which is stored in the env_data/data/ginkgo_data_2021.csv, the following code should be used.

require(here)
read.csv(here("data", "ginkgo_data_2021.csv"))

To load the packages which we want to load, we can just use require() and library()

require(palmerpenguins)

Data Structures:

Required Functions: c() length() matrix() data.frame()

Length description: length()

The length() function allows you to get or set the length of vectors and factors. Getting the length is useful for counting the number of entries in a column of a dataframe, which might help you figure out the number of samples in your data. Example of counting the number of entries in a column of a dataframe

require(here)
## Loading required package: here
## here() starts at /Users/UMass/Eco602/data/env_data
ginkgo <- read.csv(here("data", "ginkgo_data_2021.csv"))
length(ginkgo$max_width)
## [1] 756

The length() function determines how many elements are in a vector.

Vector c() example

num_vec  = c(1, 4, 8, 9, 13)

The length function will give an output of the number of values in our example vector

length(num_vec)
## [1] 5

matrix()

A Matrix is created using the matrix() function. Syntax The basic syntax for creating a matrix in R is 

matrix(data, nrow, ncol, byrow, dimnames)

Following is the description of the parameters used

  • data is the input vector which becomes the data elements of the matrix.

  • nrow is the number of rows to be created.

  • ncol is the number of columns to be created.

  • byrow is a logical clue. If TRUE then the input vector elements are arranged by row.

  • dimname is the names assigned to the rows and columns.

to use the num_vec vector from the previous example to create a matrix that has five rows and four columns

test_matrix <- matrix(num_vec, nrow= 5, ncol= 3)
test_matrix
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    1    1
## [2,]    4    4    4
## [3,]    8    8    8
## [4,]    9    9    9
## [5,]   13   13   13

to create a matrix with the num_vec vector that is filled row-wise rather than

test_matrix_2 <- matrix(num_vec, byrow= TRUE, nrow= 1)
test_matrix_2
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]
## [1,]    1    4    8    9   13

data.frame()

The data.frame() function is used to construct a data frame. A data frame can contain a combination of different vectors, matrices, and arguments. * A data frame can contain different types of data such as numerical, logical, and character data. * The columns in a data frame each contain one value from the variables and each row contains one set of values from each column. * All elements in a column have the same data type but different columns can have different data types.

Using row.names with data.frame()

num_vec  = c(1, 4, 8, 9, 13)
test_matrix <- matrix(num_vec, nrow= 5, ncol= 3)
data.frame(test_matrix, row.names = c("a", "b", "c", "d", "e"))
##   X1 X2 X3
## a  1  1  1
## b  4  4  4
## c  8  8  8
## d  9  9  9
## e 13 13 13

Numerical Data Exploration

Use the ginkgo or Palmer penguin data to create examples of:

  • summary() - It is used to produce result summaries of the results of various model fitting functions.
  • mean() - It is calculated by taking the sum of the values and dividing with the number of values in a data series. The function mean() is used to calculate this in R.
  • sd() - This function computes the standard deviation of the values in x. If na.rm is TRUE then missing values are removed before computation proceeds.

For example:

summary(ginkgo)

Graphical Data Exploration:

Visual data exploration is a mandatory intial step whether or not more formal analysis follows. When combined with descriptive statistics, visualization provides an effective way to identify summaries, structure, relationships, differences, and abnormalities in the data.

Scatterplot:

Using the ginkgo data, create a scatterplot of max leaf depth (x) and max leaf width (y)

plot(x = ginkgo$max_depth, y = ginkgo$max_width, 
     xlab = "Max Depth", ylab = "Max Width", main = "Dimension of Ginkgo leaves")

Plot using all arguments:

plot(x = ginkgo$max_depth, y = ginkgo$max_width, 
     xlab = "Max Depth", ylab = "Max Width", main = "Dimension of Ginkgo leaves", type = "p", col = "5", pch = 16, cex = 1.5, xlim = c(0, max(ginkgo$max_depth)+20), ylim = c(0, max(ginkgo$max_width)+20))

plot() required arguments:

  • col = In R, the color black is denoted by col = 1 in most plotting functions, red is denoted by col = 2 , and green is denoted by col = 3 . So if youre plotting multiple groups of things, its natural to plot them using colors 1, 2, and 3

  • pch = The default R plot pch symbol is 1, which is an empty circle. You can change this to pch = 19 (solid circle) or to pch = 21 (filled circle). To change the color and the size of points, use the following arguments: col : color (hexadecimal color code or color name)

  • cex = number indicating the amount by which plotting text and symbols should be scaled relative to the default. 1=default, 1.5 is 50% larger, 0.5 is 50% smaller, etc

  • main = used to create a title Example: main = Title of Graph

  • xlab = used to label the x axis

  • example: xlab = This is my x title

  • ylab = used to label the y axis

  • xlim = used to set limits of the x axis. Ex: c(0, max(ginkgo$max_depth)+20)

  • ylim = used to set limits of the y axis

Histogram

(hist()) is used to create a histogram of data frame.

example of penguin flipper lengths histogram

hist(penguins$flipper_length_mm, xlab = "Flipper length", main = "Penguin Flipper Length", breaks = 4)

Required arguments

breaks shows the breaks, which are the cutoff points for the bins. It shows the counts, intensity/density for each bin ( same thing but two different names for R version compatibility ), the midpoints of each bin, and then the name of the variable, whether the bins are equidistant, and the class of the object.

Boxplot

  • Two examples using the ginkgo data:

a simple boxplot of ginkgo petiole lengths

boxplot(ginkgo$petiole_length, main = "Ginkgo Petiole Length")

conditional boxplot of one of the continuous variables conditioned on the seeds_present column

boxplot(data = ginkgo, max_width ~ seeds_present, "Max width by Seeds present", xlab = "Seeds Presence", ylab = "Max Leaf Width")

Create a 4-panel figure of histograms, arranged in a 2 by 2 grid. * Require function -> par() * Required arguments -> mfrow = c(...,...)

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
boxplot(ginkgo$petiole_length, main = "Ginkgo Petiole Length")
boxplot(ginkgo$max_width, main = "Ginkgo Maximum Width")
boxplot(ginkgo$notch_depth, main = "Ginkgo Notch Depth")
boxplot(ginkgo$max_depth, main = "Ginkgo Maximum Depth")

Distribution Functions:

dnorm, pnorm, qnorm and rnorm are used to pull numbers from a normal distribution.

dnorm calculates the probability density (or mass) of a single event based on a normally distributed population, for example the probability of observing a sample mean 4.3cm for penguin flipper length.

pnorm can be used to calculate the probability of observing values on above or below a critical value when calculating a confidence interval.

qnorm() calculates the quantile for a given value in a normal distribution. The mean and standard deviation of the distribution must be provided.

dbinom() calculates the probability of an exact given value occurring in a binomial distribution. The size and probability must be provided.

dnorm()

example: It finds the value of y (height of the curve) for a given value of x. The mean and standard deviation of the distribution must be provided.

dnorm(1.5, mean = 0, sd = 1)
## [1] 0.1295176

pnorm()

example: It finds the probability of the given value OR LESS occurring. The mean and standard deviation of the distribution must be provided.

pnorm(1.5, mean = 0, sd = 1)
## [1] 0.9331928

To find the probability of the given value OR MORE, use the lower.tail = FALSE option.

pnorm(1.5, mean = 0, sd = 1, lower.tail = FALSE)
## [1] 0.0668072

qnorm()

example: The mean and standard deviation of the distribution must be provided.

qnorm(0.85,mean=70,sd=3)
## [1] 73.1093

_binom

The _binom functions work to generate the binomial distribution with the density, distribution, and quantile functions as well as with random number generation using parameters size and prob. This is conventionally interpreted as the number of successes in size trials.

  • dbinom(): the probability mass function - dbinom () calculates the probability of an exact given value occurring in a binomial distribution. The size and probability must be provided.
dbinom(x = 1:10, size = 10, prob = 0.2)
##  [1] 0.2684354560 0.3019898880 0.2013265920 0.0880803840 0.0264241152
##  [6] 0.0055050240 0.0007864320 0.0000737280 0.0000040960 0.0000001024
# Grid of X-axis values
x <- 1:80

# size = 80, prob = 0.2
plot(dbinom(x, size = 80, prob = 0.2), type = "h", lwd = 2,
     main = "Binomial probability function",
     ylab = "P(X = x)", xlab = "Number of successes")

# size = 80, prob = 0.3
lines(dbinom(x, size = 80, prob = 0.3), type = "h",
      lwd = 2, col = rgb(1,0,0, 0.7))

# size = 80, prob = 0.4
lines(dbinom(x, size = 80, prob = 0.4), type = "h",
      lwd = 2, col = rgb(0, 1, 0, 0.7))

# Add a legend
legend("topright", legend = c("80  0.2", "80  0.3", "80  0.4"),
       title = "size  prob", title.adj = 0.95,
       lty = 1, col = 1:3, lwd = 2, box.lty = 0)

  • pbinom(): the cumulative mass function In order to calculate the probability of a variable XX following a binomial distribution taking values lower than or equal to xx you can use the pbinom function, which arguments are described below:
pbinom(q,                 # Quantile or vector of quantiles
       size,              # Number of trials (n > = 0)
       prob,              # The probability of success on each trial
       lower.tail = TRUE, # If TRUE, probabilities are P(X <= x), or P(X > x) otherwise
       log.p = FALSE)     # If TRUE, probabilities are given as log
pbinom(6, size = 20, prob = 0.4) # 0.2500107 or 25%
## [1] 0.2500107
1 - pbinom(6, size = 20, prob = 0.4, lower.tail = FALSE) # Equivalent
## [1] 0.2500107
binom_sum(size = 20, prob = 0.4, ub = 6, lwd = 2,
          ylab = "P(X = x)", xlab = "Number of successes")

example code:

pbinom(3, size = 10, prob = 0.3)
## [1] 0.6496107
# Grid of X-axis values
x <- 1:80

# size = 80, prob = 0.2
plot(pbinom(x, size = 80, prob = 0.2), type = "s", lwd = 2,
     main = "Binomial distribution function",
     xlab = "Number of successes", ylab = "F(x)")

# size = 80, prob = 0.3
lines(pbinom(x, size = 80, prob = 0.3), type = "s",
      lwd = 2, col = 2)

# size = 80, prob = 0.4
lines(pbinom(x, size = 80, prob = 0.4), type = "s",
      lwd = 2, col = 3)

# Add a legend
legend("bottomright", legend = c("80  0.2", "80  0.3", "80  0.4"),
       title = "size  prob", title.adj = 0.95,
       lty = 1, col = 1:3, lwd = 2, box.lty = 0)

  • qbinom(): the quantile function The binomial quantile function can be plotted in R for a set of probabilities, a number of trials and a probability of success with the following code:
# Grid of X-axis values
x <- 1:80

# size = 80, prob = 0.2
plot(qbinom(seq(0, 1, 0.001), size = 80, prob = 0.2),
     main = "Binomial quantile function",
     ylab = "Q(p)", xlab = "p",
     type = "s", col = 3, xaxt = "n")
axis(1, labels = seq(0, 1, 0.1), at = 0:10 * 100)

# size = 80, prob = 0.3
lines(qbinom(seq(0, 1, 0.001), size = 80, prob = 0.3), type = "s", col = 2)

# size = 80, prob = 0.4
lines(qbinom(seq(0, 1, 0.001), size = 80, prob = 0.4), type = "s", col = 1)

# Add a legend
legend("topleft", legend = c("80  0.2", "80  0.3", "80  0.4"),
       title = "size  prob", title.adj = 0.95,
       lty = 1, col = 1:3, lwd = 2, box.lty = 0)
